    Based on the provided error message, stack trace, and code analysis,        
    here's the full root cause and fix:                                         
                                                                                
                              Program State Analysis                            
                                                                                
     1 Input: The program processes a define function with 32 explicitly        
       declared arrays (p1, p2, ..., p38) followed by 52 more p-prefixed        
       variables (p39 to p68) — a total of 84 variable names.                   
     2 Initialization Flow:                                                     
        • v_count (variable count) is 96 (confirmed via print v_count).         
        • a_count (array count) is 32 (confirmed via print a_count).            
        • STORE_INCR is likely 32 based on the code (a_count += STORE_INCR).    
        • The more_arrays() function is called to grow the arrays and a_names   
          buffers.                                                              
        • old_count = a_count = 32 (before increment).                          
        • a_count is updated to 32 + 32 = 64.                                   
        • New buffers of size 64 are allocated.                                 
     3 Critical Defect:                                                         
        • After copying old arrays: for (indx = 1; indx < old_count; indx++) →  
          indx ends at 32.                                                      
        • The next loop: for (; indx < v_count; indx++) runs from indx = 32 to  
          indx = 96, writing to arrays[32], arrays[33], ..., up to arrays[95].  
        • But the allocated arrays array only has size 64, so indices 64 to 95  
          are out of bounds — heap buffer overflow.                             
     4 Why the crash:                                                           
        • The loop writes 32 extra elements (32 to 95) into a buffer of size    
          64.                                                                   
        • This corrupts heap metadata and/or adjacent memory.                   
        • Later, when the program tries to access or free these buffers (e.g.   
          during cleanup or lookup), the corrupted heap state triggers a        
          runtime detection (e.g. AddressSanitizer), crashing the program.      
     5 Root Cause of Logic Error:                                               
        • The loop initialization uses v_count (total variable count) — which   
          applies to all variables, not just arrays.                            
        • However, the array buffer (arrays) is sized only for a_count (array   
          count).                                                               
        • Since v_count > a_count, and the loop assumes all variable indices    
          are valid array indices, it overwrites memory.                        
                                                                                
                                   ROOT CAUSE:                                  
                                                                                
    bc/storage.c:176 uses v_count (variable count) as the loop upper bound      
    when initializing new array elements, but the arrays buffer was only        
    allocated to hold a_count elements. Since v_count (96) exceeds a_count      
    (32), the loop writes past the end of the allocated heap buffer, causing a  
    heap buffer overflow.                                                       
                                                                                
                                    LOCAL FIX:                                  
                                                                                
    Replace v_count with a_count in the for loop upper bound to ensure we only  
    write within the allocated array size.                                      
                                                                                
                                                                                
     // Before                                                                  
     for (; indx < v_count; indx++)                                             
         arrays[indx] = NULL;                                                   
                                                                                
     // After                                                                   
     for (; indx < a_count; indx++)                                             
         arrays[indx] = NULL;                                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
                                   GLOBAL FIX:                                  
                                                                                
    The fundamental issue is that v_count and a_count serve different           
    purposes:                                                                   
                                                                                
     • v_count = total number of variable names (including non-array            
       variables).                                                              
     • a_count = size of the arrays buffer.                                     
                                                                                
    The function more_arrays() is designed to grow the array buffer for array   
    variables. Therefore, initialization should only proceed up to a_count,     
    not v_count.                                                                
                                                                                
    A more robust design would:                                                 
                                                                                
     • Separate variable name tracking from array indexing.                     
     • Use a single buffer for all variables (a_names), and only use arrays     
       for array state.                                                         
     • Use a_count for array buffer sizing and iteration.                       
                                                                                
    But for minimal correctness, the local fix suffices.                        
                                                                                
    ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────  
    ROOT CAUSE: bc/storage.c:176 uses v_count (total variable count) as the     
    loop upper bound when initializing new arrays elements, but the buffer was  
    allocated with size a_count (array count). Since v_count > a_count, the     
    loop writes past the allocated buffer, corrupting heap metadata and         
    causing a crash.                                                            
                                                                                
    LOCAL FIX:                                                                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
     // Replace this line:                                                      
     for (; indx < v_count; indx++)                                             
         arrays[indx] = NULL;                                                   
                                                                                
     // With this:                                                              
     for (; indx < a_count; indx++)                                             
         arrays[indx] = NULL;                                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
    GLOBAL FIX: Refactor the code to track array buffer size (a_count)          
    separately from variable count (v_count). Ensure that allocation and        
    initialization depend only on a_count, not on v_count, to eliminate         
    confusion between variable names and array indices.                         
